        },
        {
            "type": "title",
            "bbox": [
                0.111,
                0.635,
                0.833,
                0.682
            ],
            "angle": 0,
            "content": "3.6 Algorithm to calculate indirect financial percentages in complex group structures"
        },
        {
            "type": "text",
            "bbox": [
                0.11,
                0.703,
                0.875,
                0.769
            ],
            "angle": 0,
            "content": "Mathematics and graphs theory in particular bring an interesting contribution to a difficult situation in consolidation. Indeed, whatever complex can be the structure of a group, there exists an algorithm that calculates the indirect financial percentages."
        },
        {
            "type": "text",
            "bbox": [
                0.11,
                0.783,
                0.876,
                0.833
            ],
            "angle": 0,
            "content": "Most of consolidation software provide this function but for groups with a limited number of companies, it is also quite easy to develop that algorithm in a spreadsheet as we explain hereunder."
        },
        {
            "type": "text",
            "bbox": [
                0.11,
                0.847,
                0.825,
                0.865
            ],
            "angle": 0,
            "content": "We will give the explanation on the basis of the following group structure."
        }
    ],
    [
        {
            "type": "header",
            "bbox": [
                0.111,
                0.061,
                0.364,
                0.077
            ],
            "angle": 0,
            "content": "DIRECT CONSOLIDATION"
        },
        {
            "type": "image",
            "bbox": [
                0.116,
                0.112,
                0.396,
                0.288
            ],
            "angle": 0,
            "content": null
        },
        {
            "type": "text",
            "bbox": [
                0.407,
                0.116,
                0.883,
                0.182
            ],
            "angle": 0,
            "content": "The answer we want to get through the algorithm is \\(86\\% = 80\\% + 60\\% * 10\\%\\) for A, \\(60\\%\\) for B and \\(56.4\\% = 80\\% * 40\\% + 60\\% * 10\\% * 40\\% + 60\\% * 20\\% + 10\\%\\) for C."
        },
        {
            "type": "text",
            "bbox": [
                0.107,
                0.309,
                0.882,
                0.341
            ],
            "angle": 0,
            "content": "We first build a matrix with direct percentages between companies. Let's call D that matrix."
        },
        {
            "type": "table",
            "bbox": [
                0.251,
                0.351,
                0.735,
                0.445
            ],
            "angle": 0,
            "content": "<table><tr><td>P</td><td>A</td><td>B</td><td>C</td></tr><tr><td colspan=\"4\"></td></tr><tr><td>0</td><td>0.8</td><td>0.6</td><td>0.1</td></tr><tr><td>0</td><td>0</td><td>0</td><td>0.4</td></tr><tr><td>0</td><td>0.1</td><td>0</td><td>0.2</td></tr><tr><td>0</td><td>0</td><td>0</td><td>0</td></tr></table>"
        },
        {
            "type": "text",
            "bbox": [
                0.107,
                0.47,
                0.667,
                0.486
            ],
            "angle": 0,
            "content": "For instance, company B owns \\(20\\% = 0.2\\) in company C."
        },
        {
            "type": "text",
            "bbox": [
                0.106,
                0.503,
                0.88,
                0.534
            ],
            "angle": 0,
            "content": "We then define the unit matrix called \\(\\mathbf{I}\\) with 1 on the diagonal and 0 in all the other cells"
        },
        {
            "type": "table",
            "bbox": [
                0.304,
                0.538,
                0.731,
                0.607
            ],
            "angle": 0,
            "content": "<table><tr><td>1</td><td>0</td><td>0</td><td>0</td></tr><tr><td>0</td><td>1</td><td>0</td><td>0</td></tr><tr><td>0</td><td>0</td><td>1</td><td>0</td></tr><tr><td>0</td><td>0</td><td>0</td><td>1</td></tr></table>"
        },
        {
            "type": "text",
            "bbox": [
                0.107,
                0.632,
                0.445,
                0.649
            ],
            "angle": 0,
            "content": "and calculate \\(\\mathbb{I} - \\mathbb{D}\\) in order to get"
        },
        {
            "type": "table",
            "bbox": [
                0.304,
                0.658,
                0.731,
                0.726
            ],
            "angle": 0,
            "content": "<table><tr><td>1</td><td>-0.8</td><td>-0.6</td><td>-0.1</td></tr><tr><td>0</td><td>1</td><td>0</td><td>-0.4</td></tr><tr><td>0</td><td>-0.1</td><td>1</td><td>-0.2</td></tr><tr><td>0</td><td>0</td><td>0</td><td>1</td></tr></table>"
        },
        {
            "type": "text",
            "bbox": [
                0.106,
                0.745,
                0.879,
                0.779
            ],
            "angle": 0,
            "content": "Now, this matrix has to be inverted. It is a function provided by Microsoft Excel ©. We get INV(I - D)"
        },
        {
            "type": "table",
            "bbox": [
                0.304,
                0.79,
                0.731,
                0.858
            ],
            "angle": 0,
            "content": "<table><tr><td>1</td><td>0.86</td><td>0.6</td><td>0.56</td></tr><tr><td>0</td><td>1</td><td>0</td><td>0.4</td></tr><tr><td>0</td><td>0.1</td><td>1</td><td>0.24</td></tr><tr><td>0</td><td>0</td><td>0</td><td>1</td></tr></table>"
        }
    ],
    [
        {
            "type": "header",
            "bbox": [
                0.305,
                0.071,
                0.855,
                0.088
            ],
            "angle": 0,
            "content": "PART 2 BASICS OF CONSOLIDATION TECHNIQUES"
        },
        {
            "type": "text",
            "bbox": [
                0.109,
                0.119,
                0.768,
                0.135
            ],
            "angle": 0,
            "content": "Using the Excel syntax, each cell of this matrix is defined as follows"
        },
        {
            "type": "equation",
            "bbox": [
                0.322,
                0.15,
                0.662,
                0.169
            ],
            "angle": 0,
            "content": "\\[\n= I N D E X (I N V E R S E (A: B); L I N E, C O L)\n\\]"
        },
        {
            "type": "text",
            "bbox": [
                0.108,
                0.183,
                0.876,
                0.217
            ],
            "angle": 0,
            "content": "where \"A:B\" is the range defining the matrix to be inverted. \"LINE\" is the line number and \"COL\" is the column number of the cell in the output matrix."
        },
        {
            "type": "text",
            "bbox": [
                0.108,
                0.232,
                0.876,
                0.266
            ],
            "angle": 0,
            "content": "Finally, we calculate the product of both matrices \\( D \\) and \\( \\text{INV}(I - D) \\) which gives the expected result."
        },
        {
            "type": "image",
            "bbox": [
                0.284,
                0.29,
                0.749,
                0.384
            ],
            "angle": 0,
            "content": null
        },
        {
            "type": "text",
            "bbox": [
                0.109,
                0.409,
                0.876,
                0.443
            ],
            "angle": 0,
            "content": "This again is easy to calculate in Excel by using the following syntax for each cell of the output matrix"
        },
        {
            "type": "equation",
            "bbox": [
                0.309,
                0.456,
                0.679,
                0.475
            ],
            "angle": 0,
            "content": "\\[\n= I N D E X (M M U L T (A: B; C: D); L I N E; C O L)\n\\]"
        },
        {
            "type": "text",
            "bbox": [
                0.109,
                0.489,
                0.876,
                0.539
            ],
            "angle": 0,
            "content": "where \"A:B\" is the range of the matrix D, \"C:D\" is the range of the inverse matrix we just calculated and \"LINE\" and \"COL\" are the line and the column number of the corresponding cell of the final matrix."
        },
        {
            "type": "text",
            "bbox": [
                0.109,
                0.553,
                0.876,
                0.603
            ],
            "angle": 0,
            "content": "Of course, we are interested only in the first line of that matrix which gives the indirect percentages from P in all other subsidiaries. For instance, we see indeed that P owns indirectly \\(60\\%\\) in B."
        },
        {
            "type": "text",
            "bbox": [
                0.109,
                0.618,
                0.876,
                0.683
            ],
            "angle": 0,
            "content": "This algorithm works for any structure of any size. Crossed participations or cycle of participations (A -> B -> C -> A) are also accepted. The only restriction is that a subsidiary cannot own shares of the parent company. If so, that link must be ignored."
        }
    ],
